We recommended that the Management take the following courses of action:
Submit to the Audit Team the lacking documents for our review and evaluation, otherwise, the transactions will be suspended in audit; 

Submit valid comment on the inability of the Management to issue immediately Notice of Award (NOA), contract and Notice to Proceed (NTP) for the procurement of consultancy services (Disbursement Voucher (DV) No. 1002019051176).

We recommended that the:
Local Chief Executive (LCE) instruct the Inventory Committee to conduct of actual count, validation, verification and inspection of PPE owned by the Municipality to establish their existence;
Inventory Committee and Municipal Accounting Office reconcile variance/discrepancy between the RPCPPE and accounting records;
Inventory Committee submit the RPCPPE to the Auditor in prescribed format, not later than January 31 of each year;
Municipal Accounting Office maintain and update the PPELCs;
Office of the Municipal Treasurer/General Services Officer maintain and update its Property Cards; and
Office of the Municipal Treasurer/General Services Officer and Municipal Accounting Office perform periodic reconciliation of Property Cards and PPELCs and ensure that all discrepancies are immediately investigated and addressed.

We recommended that:
The Accounting Unit evaluate each item of PPE to determine whether the new capitalization threshold of ₱50,000.00 shall be applied individually or in aggregate (such as in the case of Information and Communication Technology Equipment);
After such evaluation, determine the total amount of tangible items acquired and issued prior to CY 2022 with amounts from ₱15,000.00 to below ₱50,000.00 (as well as those below ₱15,000.00) which can be derecognized from the books;
Before any derecognition, the general services officer document first the accountability over these tangible items acquired and issued prior to CY 2022 with amounts from ₱15,000.00 to below ₱50,000.00 (as well as those below ₱15,000.00) through duly signed ICSs. The issuance of ICSs should be based on available but reliable alternative records of the LGU;
The Accounting Unit and general services officer coordinate and ensure that accountabilities over these properties were established before any derecognition;
The General Services Officer prepare and maintain the RegSPI for each class of semi-expendable property (low-valued items and high-value items) by fund; and
Prospectively, the general services officer secure and maintain the following:
The ICSs of the tangible items acquired and issued prior to CY 2022 with amounts from ₱15,000.00 to below ₱50,000.00 (as well as those below ₱15,000.00) which were derecognized from the books;
The ICSs of tangible items which meet the definition and recognition criteria of PPE but cost is below ₱50,000.00 (semi-expendable property) acquired during CY 2022 and onwards;
The PARs of tangible items acquired during CY 2022 and onwards recognized as PPE; and
The RegSPI for each class of semi-expendable property (low-valued items and high-value items) by fund.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Accounting Office prepare the Aging of Accounts Payable as at year-end and submit the same as accompanying schedule to the FS;
The Municipal Accounting Office determine the validity of the Accounts Payable amounting to ₱2,568,764.04 which had already been outstanding for two years or more and which no actual claims were filed as at December 31, 2022;
When no legitimate claim against the LGU was found, the Municipal Accounting Office cause the reversion of the same to the unappropriated surplus; and
The LCE, in coordination with concerned offices, consider implementing internal control measures aimed at preventing the accumulation of long outstanding payables and ensuring its timely settlement.

We recommended that:
The LCE direct the concerned offices/implementing units to hasten the implementation of the partially and unimplemented PPAs under 20 per cent DF of CY 2022;
The LCE together with the Municipal Development Council ensure that only the development projects which are well-planned and procurement-and-implementation-ready are appropriated with funds under the 20 per cent DF as mandated by Section 3.2.3 of the DBM-DOF-DILG JMC No. 1 dated November 4, 2020;
Subject to availability of appropriation and funds, the LCE consider reinforcing the manpower of the MEO by hiring additional engineers to ensure that PPAs targeted under 20 per cent DF are given priority as to the preparation of POWs and its implementation since the inclusion of such PPAs in the budget attest to the fact of its importance and urgency; and
Prospectively, enhance the utilization of the 20 per cent DF as enjoined in AO No. 103 series of 2004 of the Office of the President and DBM-DOF-DILG JMC No. 1 dated November 4, 2020.

We recommended that the Management:

Require the Municipal Engineering Office (MEO) to provide the concerned offices, the Municipal Treasury (MT), Inventory Committee, and Municipal Accounting Office (MAccO), of available records pertaining to local road networks with complete description and cost segregation to enable reconciliation of respective existing records and, prospectively, to facilitate the preparation of required reports and records in the format prescribed under COA Circular No. 2015-008;

Direct the MT to prepare and maintain the Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components, including Road Map. Moreover, ensure that the Report on Local Road Network be prepared by the MT at the end of accounting period;

Require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of its road networks in order to ascertain the existence of the balance of the account Road Networks;

Reconcile the reports and records of MT and Inventory Committee with the MAccO to ensure the fair presentation of the Road Networks account in the Financial Statements (FS);


Ensure to compute for the depreciation of these Road Networks and draw the necessary journal entry to take up the adjustments pertaining to the unrecorded current year and prior years’ depreciation to present fairly the FS; and

Adequately provide the required disclosure pertaining to Road Networks in the Notes to FS.

We recommended that the Management:
Ensure submission of all perfected contracts and its supporting documents for auditorial and technical review to the COA within five working days from the date of perfection of such contracts;

Strictly check the completeness of the perfected contracts and its supporting documents before its submission to the COA in order to avoid delays in the conduct of the auditorial and technical review;

Ensure submission of request for technical inspection of completed infrastructure projects; 


Submit immediately the 19 perfected contracts for auditorial and technical review and request for technical inspection of the 19 completed infrastructure projects; and

Prospectively, ensure compliance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2009-001 on auditorial and technical review, and technical inspection.

We recommended that the Management take the following courses of actions:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to draft a demand letter to be issued to the concerned barangays for immediate submission of the required liquidation documents; 


Upon receipt of the liquidation documents require a representative from the Office of the Municipal Engineer to conduct inspection and validate the reported completed projects;

Require all transfer of funds to Barangays, to implement the projects and programs of the Municipality, be covered by a Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) and other documentary requirements as enumerated in Section 3.1.1 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 to establish proper accountability and monitoring of the proper utilization of the funds; and

Prospectively, fund transfers must be supported with certification by the Municipal Accountant that funds previously transferred to the Implementing Agency (IA) has been liquidated and accounted for in the books.

