Draw up implementation timelines to serve as guide in monitoring status of the project to effect prompt attainment of program objectives;

Coordinate with the Source Agencies on the proper disposition of unspent balances of completed projects;

Effect necessary adjusting entries on the transfer of completed projects; and

Prospectively, ensure that necessary documentations of fund transfers are well-kept, especially for fund transfers, to immediately determine proper disposition of said funds.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:

Discontinue the practice of giving of donations, contributions, grants in a form of financial assistance to civic organization, private associations and related organizations;



Discontinue the practice of disbursing funds from lump-sum appropriations without prior authority from the Sanggunian;



Enforce COA Circular No. 2012-003 that prohibit the payment of Irregular, Unnecessary, Unconscionable, Excessive and Extravagant Expenditures to avoid future disallowance in audit; and 

Submit justification on the release of funds from lump sum appropriation despite absence of SB authorization.

We recommended that following courses of action:

Strictly implement an effective internal control system in the procurement and disbursement process relative to infrastructure projects to avoid deficiencies and promote good governance;



Require the BAC to post the NOA, NTP and approved Contract in the PhilGEPS website to promote transparency in the procurement process; 

Ensure that the documents that form part of the contract are complete and the contract agreement provides provisions for warranty and liquidated damages;

Performance security must be dated and posted within 10 days after receipt of NOA and prior to the signing of the contract;

The Municipal Engineer must strictly monitor the implementation of projects and require the contractor to complete the project within the stipulated period in the contract, otherwise, impose applicable sanctions and penalties, if warranted;

Submit the incomplete supporting documents noted in the disbursement process to determine the validity, legality and propriety of transactions; and



Submit on time the requests for contract review and technical inspection of projects with complete supporting documents.

We therefore recommended the following courses of action:

Install and implement strict internal control in the disbursement of funds to effectively monitor and determine whether or not the funds were utilized for its intended purpose and that expenses incurred were appropriately charged to fund;

Ensure that claims against government funds are supported with complete documents before payment of the same. The Municipal Accountant should not process transactions that are not properly supported with the required documents;

Advise the LSB that in the preparation of budget, reflect and identify the specific PPAs and programmed obligations by object of expenditure with proper account codes; and

Submit immediately the deficiencies noted enumerated in Annex L.

We recommended that Management: 

Create an Inventory and Disposal Committee and appraise the market value of the unserviceable properties;



Dispose the unserviceable properties in accordance with the most appropriate mode of disposition of property as provided in Section 79 of R.A. No. 7160 which are either through (a) public auction; (b) sale through negotiation; (c) transfer without cost to other offices or departments or other government agencies; or (d) by destruction;

Facilitate the immediate disposal of the aforementioned unserviceable properties to recoup any salvage value thereof; and  

Ensure proper safekeeping of the unserviceable properties to avoid further deterioration.

